We begin by honoring the great Brice Taylor. Born without a left hand, Taylor overcame societal and physical barriers to become our first football All-American, and the first African-American football player at USC.

After his playing days, Taylor was named the Head Football Coach and Athletic Director at HBCU Southern University in Louisiana, where he led the Jaguars to their first undefeated season.

After that season, Taylor returned to Los Angeles and took the reins of Jefferson High School‚Äôs football program. In doing this, he became the first black head high school football coach in our city‚Äôs history.

Taylor went on to earn his doctorate degree and become a pastor at First African Methodist Episcopal Church in Los Angeles, the city he‚Äôd spend the rest of his life in.

Brice Taylor‚Äôs story is one of courage, strength, and leadership. He‚Äôs an example to all of us of what it means to be a true Trojan. ‚úåÔ∏è
